<TITLE> Brazil's defense minister replaced after air crash </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 BRASILIA, July 25 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Brazilian President Luiz Inacio Lula da Silva will replace his minister in charge of air travel after nearly 200 people died in the country's worst air crash last week, two presidential aides told Reuters on Wednesday. Nelson Jobim, a retired Supreme Court justice with close ties to the president, will take over as defense minister, becoming the top official in charge of Brazil's military-controlled air traffic system. Waldir Pires will step down as defense minister after two deadly air crashes in less than a year and months of chaos in the air traffic system. Pires has been under pressure for months to resign. His handling of the aviation crisis has been widely criticized as inefficient, but Lula had been reluctant to dismiss him. The sources said Jobim would be sworn in later on Wednesday. The shake-up comes one week after an Airbus A320 flown by TAM Linhas Aereas skidded off a rain-slicked runway at Sao Paulo's Congonhas Airport and crashed into a cargo terminal and gas station. All 187 people on board and at least 12 on the ground were killed in the worst aviation accident in Brazil's histo
